{{Infobox book | name = Germs: Biological Weapons and America's Secret War | title_orig = | translator = | image = Germs - Biological Weapons and America's Secret War.jpg | image_size = 193px | caption = | author = Judith Miller, Stephen Engelberg, William J. Broad | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Biological warfare]] | genre = Nonfiction | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | pub_date = October 2, 2001 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Hardcover | pages = 382 | isbn = 0-684-87158-0 | dewey = 358/.38/0973 21 | congress = UG447.8 .M54 2001 | oclc = 47182085 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Germs: Biological Weapons and America's Secret War''''' (2001)<ref name="simonandschuster">{{cite web|url=http://books.simonandschuster.com/9780743547567|title=Germs Biological Weapons and America's Secret War |publisher=simonandschuster.com|accessdate=2009-02-23}}</ref> describes how [[World population|humanity]] has dealt with [[biological warfare|biological weapons]], and the dangers of [[bioterrorism]]. It was written by ''[[The New York Times]]'' journalists [[Judith Miller (journalist)|Judith Miller]], Stephen Engelberg, and [[William Broad]] and was the [[New York Times Non-Fiction Bestsellers of 2001|2001 ''New York Times'' #1 Non-Fiction Bestseller]] the weeks of October 28 and November 4.<ref name="hawes">{{cite web|url=http://www.hawes.com/2001/2001-11-04.pdf|title=The New York Times Best Seller List|date=November 4, 2001|publisher=hawes.com|page=2|accessdate=2009-02-23}}</ref>
==Overview== ''Germs'', is a work of [[investigative journalism]] employing biographical and historical narrative to provide context.<ref name="nytimes">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05EFD81F3DF937A25753C1A9679C8B63|title=No Place to Hide |last=Rose|first=Gideon|date=October 14, 2001|publisher=nytimes.com|accessdate=2009-02-23}}</ref> The three authors interviewed hundreds of scientists and senior U.S. officials, and reviewed recently [[declassified]] documents, and reports from the [[Post-Soviet states|former Soviet Union]]'s bioweapons laboratories.
==Summary== {{Quote box | quote =''"[[Germ theory of disease|Germs]] were always what I call the [[Caboose]] of the [[Weapon of mass destruction|weapons of mass destruction]] train."'' (Judith Miller, November 18, 2001) | source =<ref name="virginia">{{cite web |url=http://www.virginia.edu/uvanewsmakers/newsmakers/miller.html |title=Judith Miller |publisher=virginia.edu |accessdate=2009-02-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071109174341/http://www.virginia.edu/uvanewsmakers/newsmakers/miller.html |archivedate=2007-11-09 |df= }}</ref> | width =25% | align =right }} The book opens with an account of the 1984 [[salmonella]] poisonings in [[The Dalles, Oregon]], caused by followers of [[Osho (Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh)|Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh]] who sprayed salmonella onto salad bars. Other research shows how [[Moscow]] scientists created an untraceable germ that would induce the body to self-destruct, and reveals that the U.S. military planned for germ warfare on [[Cuba]] during the 1960s.<ref name="simonandschuster" /> Three classified U.S. biodefense projects are detailed: [[Project Bacchus]], [[Project Clear Vision]], and [[Project Jefferson]].<ref name="Enemark">{{cite book|last=Enemark|first=Christian |title=Disease and Security|publisher=Routledge|date=April 24, 2007|edition=GoogleBook|page=173|isbn=0-415-42234-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bT9j6lhPHHUC&pg=PA173&dq=%22Project+Clear+Vision%22&client=firefox-a#PPA173,M1}}</ref> ''Germs'' concludes with an assessment of the United States' ability to deter future bio-attack.<ref name="businessweek" />
==Reviews== ''[[The New York Times Book Review]]'' was favorable, though it criticized the book's tone as "somewhat [[alarmism|alarmist]]".<ref name="nytimes" /> ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' was also generally favorable, except for pointing out some conflicting views on bioterrorism.<ref name="businessweek">{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/01_42/b3753045.htm |title=Bio-Terrorism under the Microscope |last=Arnst |first=Catherine |date=October 15, 2001 |publisher=businessweek.com |accessdate=2009-02-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215123330/http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/01_42/b3753045.htm |archivedate=2009-02-15 |df= }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'''s [[book review]] by British [[psychiatrist]] [[Simon Wessely]], cautioned against [[panic]], stating that biological weapons can cause destruction through fear, effectively giving the biodefense industry "the equivalent of a [[blank cheque]]".<ref name="guardian">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2001/oct/20/highereducation.news1|title=Germs: Biological Weapons and America's Secret War |last=Wessely|first=Simon |date=October 10, 2001|publisher=guardian.co.uk|accessdate=2009-02-23}}</ref>
